[[File:Satori.svg|thumb|right|100px| ''Satori'' in [[Japanese language|Japanese]]]] '''Satori generation''' (さとり世代) is a [[Japanese language]] neologism used to describe young Japanese who have seemingly achieved the Buddhist [[Satori|enlightened state]] free from material desires but who have in reality given up ambition and hope due to [[economy of Japan|macro-economic]] trends.<ref>[http://www.adbusters.org/article/the-satori-generation/ The Satori generation] adbusters.org</ref> The term was coined around 2010.<ref name="Michael Hoffman" /> The Satori generation are not interested in earning money, career advancement, and [[conspicuous consumption]], or even travel, hobbies and romantic relationships; their [[Drinking in Japan|alcohol consumption]] is far lower than Japanese of earlier generations.<ref name="Michael Hoffman">Michael Hoffman, [http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/03/31/national/media-national/life-is-too-short-for-an-undesirable-satori/ Life is too short for an undesirable satori] ''[[Japan Times]]'', 2013/03/31</ref> They live in a period of [[Waithood]] and are [[NEET]], [[parasite single]]s, [[freeter]]s or [[hikikomori]]. The Satori generation in Japan is roughly equivalent to the [[Sampo generation]] in Korea,<ref>Beatrix Tan, [http://rgnn.org/2015/11/23/satori-generation-the-new-age-enlightened-stoics-of-japan/ SATORI GENERATION: THE NEW-AGE ENLIGHTENED STOICS OF JAPAN] ''RGNN'', November 23, 2015</ref> and is somewhat similar to the [[Strawberry generation]] in Taiwan.
